"1357","1245":"1245","27 February 1274":"27 februari 1274","about 1245":"circa 1245","of Clayhidon, Devon, England":"Clayhidon, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1245–about October 1285":"about 1245–about October 1285","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1272–1357":"1272–1357","1215–1274":"1215–1274","about 1272":"about 1272","about October 1285":"about October 1285","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1357":"1357","1245":"1245","27 February 1274":"27 February 1274","about 1245":"about 1245","of Clayhidon, Devon, England":"Clayhidon, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hydon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Haydon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Haydon","meanings":["English (Devon) and Irish: variant of   Hayden  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Richard Hydon was born about 1245, in Devon, England as the son of John de Hydon. He had at least 1 daughter with Isabel Fishacre. He died about October 1285, at the age of 41."},"et":{"about 1245–about October 1285":"umbes 1245–umbes oktoober 1285","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1272–1357":"1272–1357","1215–1274":"1215–1274","about 1272":"umbes 1272","about October 1285":"umbes oktoober 1285","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1357":"1357","1245":"1245","27 February 1274":"27. veebruar 1274","about 1245":"umbes 1245","of Clayhidon, Devon, England":"Clayhidon, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1245–about October 1285":"noin 1245–noin lokakuu 1285","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1272–1357":"1272–135